'''''X-Wing: The Krytos Trap''''' is the third installment in the [[Star Wars: X-Wing (novel series)|''X-Wing'']] series of novels, written by [[Michael A. Stackpole]]. It was published by [[Bantam Spectra]] in [[October]] [[1996]]. Narration for the [[X-Wing: The Krytos Trap (unabridged audiobook)|audio]] version was performed by [[Henry Thomas]]. The [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Alliance to Restore the Republic]] has just captured the planet [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]] from the hands of imperial leader [[Ysanne Isard]]. But instead of a glorious victory the Rebels discover a horrible truth; The planet's non-Human population has been infected with a vicious disease called the [[Krytos virus]]. It can be cured by [[Bacta/Legends|bacta]], but the demand is too much for the planet to handle. [[Rogue Squadron/Legends|Rogue Squadron]] is assigned to attack [[Warlord/Legends|Warlord]] [[Zsinj]] and his space station that contained a healthy amount of bacta that had been stolen from a deep space convoy. The assignment is difficult, maybe impossible, but in the words of [[Corran Horn/Legends|Corran Horn]]: "Impossible is what the Rogues do best."

==Publisher's summary==
''The Rebels have taken Coruscant, but their problems are far from over. A killer virus called Krytos is wiping out the indigenous population, and a counter-revolution is exploding. At the center of the storm is the highly charged treason trial of Rebel hero Tycho Celchu. While agents provocateurs carry out their acts of terrorism, the fledging state can be defended only by the blood and courage of Rogue Squadron. As the X-wing fighters scramble to save the Rebellion, Corran Horn, given up for dead in Ysanne Isard's inescapable prison, discovers he alone holds the key to freeing Coruscant from the Empire!''

==Plot summary==
As the [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]] struggles to control the outbreak of the [[Krytos virus]] on newly conquered [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]], [[Wedge Antilles/Legends|Wedge]] must bottle his outrage over [[Tycho Celchu/Legends|Tycho Celchu's]] being placed on trial for the [[Death/Legends|murder]] of [[Corran Horn/Legends|Corran Horn]]. [[Nawara Ven]], a fellow [[Rogue Squadron/Legends|Rogue]] and former [[Lawyer/Legends|lawyer]], serves as Tycho's defense lawyer, but evidence to remove suspicion is sparse. Serving as a further distraction, Wedge must now put aside his interest in [[Iella Wessiri Antilles|Iella Wessiri]] when her husband, [[Diric Wessiri|Diric]], turns up alive and well after he was granted his freedom from [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] [[Prison/Legends|custody]] by [[Alliance Intelligence/Legends|Alliance Intelligence]].

As the case against Tycho speeds toward trial, the Rogues still carry out [[Starfighter/Legends|starfighter]] missions. Replenishing dwindling [[Bacta/Legends|bacta]] supplies is of paramount importance, so the Rogues hit a cache of bacta plundered by the Imperial [[Warlord/Legends|warlord]] [[Zsinj]] in a [[Space station/Legends|space station]] over [[Yag'Dhul/Legends|Yag'dhul]]. Later, they launch a mission to [[Ryloth/Legends|Ryloth]] to secure supplies of [[Ryll/Legends|ryll]], a medicinal agent that can alleviate the suffering caused by the Krytos virus. Meanwhile, the New Republic capital is under constant harassment from forces led by [[Kirtan Loor]]. He stokes [[Anti-Humanism|antihuman]] resentment among the [[Planet/Legends|planet's]] beleaguered [[Alien/Legends|alien]] population and scuttles bacta supplies to ensure a shortage. The ambitious Loor seeks to unseat both [[Ysanne Isard]] and the local underworld's influence on Coruscant. Loor learns that his plans are known to Isard and realizes his days are numbered. Unbeknownst to the Rogues, Corran Horn is alive and [[Prisoner/Legends|incarcerated]] at [[Lusankya (prison)|''Lusankya'']], Isard's infamous prison facility where the Empire [[Brainwashing|brainwashes]] its subjects into becoming potential [[Sleeper agent/Legends|sleeper agents]]. There, Corran meets and befriends an elder [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Alliance]] [[General/Legends|general]] named [[Jan Dodonna/Legends|Jan]]. He also learns that Tycho was never a sleeper agent. While escaping from the facility, Corran discovers that ''Lusankya'' is actually a [[Executor-class Star Dreadnought/Legends|Super Star Destroyer]] hidden beneath the surface of Coruscant. Returning to Coruscant's surface, Corran detours through a sealed [[Galactic Museum]] exhibit about the [[Jedi Order/Legends|Jedi Order]]. Here he picks up a [[Nejaa Halcyon's lightsaber|lightsaber]] and begins to learn the truth of his heritage: he is descendant of [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knight]] [[Nejaa Halcyon|Nejaa Halcyon]].

A desperate Loor tries to broker a deal with Nawara Ven. In exchange for proving Tycho's innocence, Loor wants immunity and sanctuary within the New Republic. Before Loor can be taken into custody, however, word of a high-ranking defection reaches Isard. She has a sleeper agent – Diric Wessiri – eliminate the traitor. Diric kills Loor and is in turn killed by return fire from his wife, Iella. Loor's testimony is not required as Corran returns to the Rogues and clears Tycho's name. He discovers the identity of the true traitor in the squadron: [[Erisi Dlarit]]. Isard launches the hidden Star Destroyer from beneath Coruscant's surface, and the ''Lusankya'' retreats from the capital to [[Thyferra/Legends|Thyferra]]. Erisi joins her in escape. Though the Rogues briefly celebrate the return of Corran and the reinstatement of Tycho, they are ordered by the New Republic to stay away from Thyferra for political reasons. Corran begins a tide of defection by resigning his commission, and the other Rogues follow his example. The squadron leaves the New Republic so they can pursue Isard, stop her control of the bacta cartel on Thyferra, and free the captives aboard her prison [[Warship/Legends|warship]].

==Continuity==
Though his last name was never mentioned in this book, the old [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Alliance]] [[General/Legends|general]] whom [[Corran Horn/Legends|Corran]] meets at the [[Lusankya (prison)|''Lusankya'' prison]] was [[Jan Dodonna/Legends|Jan Dodonna]], the Rebel [[Officer/Legends|officer]] who led the briefing prior to the attack on the [[DS-1 Orbital Battle Station/Legends|first Death Star]]. His presence helped solve a continuity error. The original [[Star Wars (comic strip)|''Star Wars'' newspaper comic strips]] distributed by the [[Los Angeles Times Syndicate]] from [[1981]] to [[1984]] depicted Dodonna sacrificing his life to set [[Explosive charge/Legends|explosives]] as the Rebels evacuated their base on [[Yavin 4/Legends|Yavin 4]] while escaping [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] pursuit. But in [[1992]], the [[Star Wars: Dark Empire|''Dark Empire'']] comic book series depicted Dodonna alive and well, serving as a general in the [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]], [[Standard year/Legends|years]] after the events of [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|Return of the Jedi]]. [[West End Games]]’ [[The Movie Trilogy Sourcebook|''Star Wars: The Movie Trilogy Sourcebook'']] ([[1993]]) established that he was captured on Yavin 4 and later freed by a Rebel special mission. ''The Krytos Trap'' and [[X-Wing: Isard's Revenge|''Isard's Revenge'']] ([[1999]]) would dramatize this in storytelling.<ref name="TERC" />

Before the start of the novel, the Dramatis Personae [[Rogue Squadron/Legends|Rogue Squadron]] incorrectly lists [[Captain/Legends|Captain]] [[Aril Nunb]] as a [[Humanoid/Legends|human]] male from [[Sullust/Legends|Sullust]], when she is clearly a [[Sullustan/Legends|Sullustan]] female from Sullust. On page 189 of the first run of the book (0553568035), [[Liat Tsayv]] is incorrectly written as Liat Tevv.


